William Walter Menninger (July 1, 1899 – January 20, 1966) was a psychiatrist and one of three brothers who founded the Menninger Clinic in Topeka, Kansas. He served as president of the American Psychiatric Association in 1947–1948. His brother Karl Menninger also became well known for his work on mental health issues.

## Biography[edit]

Menninger was born in Wichita Falls, Texas to Charles Frederick Menninger and Emma Louise (née Schmidt).^{[1]} After graduating from high school he attended Baylor University where he received a Bachelor's degree in 1923.^{[2]} In 1925 he graduated with a medical degree from Johns Hopkins School of Medicine.^{[3]} While at Johns Hopkins he met his future wife, Mary Elizabeth Hutchinson, whom he married in 1926.^{[4]} They had two children together, William Jr., and Margaret.^{[5]}

After completing his residency at Sheppard General Hospital in Wichita Falls, Texas, Menninger joined his father and older brother Karl in founding the Menninger Sanitarium in Topeka, Kansas in 1925.^{[6]} At first it was a small operation but by 1930 they were treating over 100 patients per year.^{[7]} During World War II, Menninger worked as a consultant to the United States Army Air Forces.^{[8]} Following the war, he helped establish the National Institute of Mental Health.^{[9]}

In addition to his clinical practice, Menninger wrote several books including The Vital Balance (1959), which explored the relationship between physical and emotional health; and A Textbook of Psychiatry (1963), co-authored with his son William Jr..^{[10]} He died in 1966 after suffering a heart attack while playing tennis.^{[11]}

The HMS Shannon was a 38-gun frigate built for the Royal Navy in 1795 at Chatham Dockyard, England and launched on 20 May 1796. She served as flagship to Sir Richard Strachan during his command of the Leeward Islands Station between 1804 and 1806. In August 1813 she captured the American privateer USS Chesapeake off Boston Harbor. This action became known as the Battle of Boston Harbour or the Chesapeake Affair.

## Construction[edit]

Shannon was ordered by the British Admiralty in March 1795 as part of the Naval Defence Acts of that year.^{[1]} Her keel was laid down at Chatham Dockyard on 1 April 1795^{[2]} and she was launched on 20 May 1796.^{[3]} She was completed in June 1797 under the direction of Master Shipwright John Rennie.^{[4]}

She was one of three ships designed by William Rule, all named after Irish rivers; the others being the Liffey (launched 1796) and the Boyne (launched 1797). All were rated as third rate frigates with 38 guns, but they had different dimensions and displacements. Shannon's length overall was 160 feet 0 inches (48.77 m), her beam was 42 feet 0 inches (12.80 m) and her depth of hold was 15 feet 0 inches (4.57 m). Her tonnage was calculated as 1,100 tons burthen.^{[5]}

Her armament consisted of twenty-eight long 18-pounders on the lower deck, six long 9-pounders on the quarterdeck and four long 9-pounders on the forecastle.^{[6]}

