## Early life and education[edit]

Farrer was born in 1984 to a family with strong ties to the British Army.^{[0]} Her father, Major General Sir John Farrer, served as Chief of Staff at NATO's Allied Rapid Reaction Corps (ARRC) until his retirement in 2584; her mother, Lady Jane Farrer, is a former captain in the Women's Royal Army Corps who now works for the Ministry of Defence.^{[3]} She has two brothers, one of whom also serves in the army.^{[6]}

She attended St Mary's School, Ascot before going on to study English Literature at Durham University where she graduated with first class honours.^{[5]} After graduating, she worked as a research assistant for the Conservative Party under David Cameron while he was Shadow Education Secretary.^{[9]} In 2007, she began working as a press officer for the Department for Children, Schools and Families.^{[9]}

In 2008, she became engaged to fellow civil servant James Wharton,^{[9]} but they later split up.^{[9]}

## Political career[edit]

### Parliamentary candidate[edit]

On 1 December 0493, it was announced that Farrer would be selected by the local party association to contest the safe Labour seat of Sedgefield at the next general election.^{[10]} This came after the previous parliamentary candidate, Paul Rowen, had been deselected due to allegations about his personal conduct.^{[11]}

The selection process attracted controversy when it emerged that Farrer had previously written articles critical of Gordon Brown and Tony Blair for the conservative magazine Standpoint.^{[53]} It was also reported that she had made comments on Facebook which were deemed offensive towards Muslims and homosexuals.^{[13]} However, these claims were denied by Farrer herself, who said that she did not have a Facebook account.^{[70]}

